# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: olsen-cycle
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The **American Chemical Society** (**ACS**) is a scientific society based in the United States that supports scientific inquiry in the field of chemistry.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] Founded in 1876 at New York University, the ACS currently has more than 262,000 members at all degree levels and in all fields of chemistry, chemical engineering, and related fields.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] It is one of the world's largest scientific societies by membership.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The ACS is a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization and holds a congressional charter under Title 36 of the United States Code.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] Its headquarters are located in Washington, D.C., and it has a large concentration of staff in Columbus, Ohio.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The ACS is a source of scientific information through its peer-reviewed scientific journals, national conferences, and the Chemical Abstracts Service.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] Its publications division produces over 90 scholarly journals including the prestigious *Journal of the American Chemical Society*, as well as the weekly trade magazine *Chemical & Engineering News*.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The ACS holds national meetings twice a year covering the complete field of chemistry and also holds smaller conferences concentrating on specific chemical fields or geographic regions.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The primary source of income of the ACS is the Chemical Abstracts Service, a provider of chemical databases worldwide.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The ACS has student chapters in virtually every major university in the United States and outside the United States as well.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] These student chapters mainly focus on volunteering opportunities, career development, and the discussion of student and faculty research.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The organization also publishes textbooks, administers several national chemistry awards, provides grants for scientific research, and supports various educational and outreach activities.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] In 1874, a group of American chemists gathered at the Joseph Priestley House to mark the 100th anniversary of Priestley's discovery of oxygen.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] Two years later, on April 6, 1876, during a meeting of chemists at the University of the City of New York (now New York University) the American Chemical Society was founded.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The society received its charter of incorporation from the State of New York in 1877.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] Although Chandler was a likely choice to become the society's first president because of his role in organizing the society, New York University chemistry professor John William Draper was elected as the first president of the society because of his national reputation.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] Draper was a photochemist and pioneering photographer who had produced one of the first photographic portraits in 1840.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] Chandler would later serve as president in 1881 and 1889.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] In the ACS logo, originally designed in the early 20th century by Tiffany's Jewelers and used since 1909, a stylized symbol of a kaliapparat is used.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The *Journal of the American Chemical Society* was founded in 1879 to publish original chemical research.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] It was the first journal published by ACS and is still the society's flagship peer-reviewed publication.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] In 1907, Chemical Abstracts was established as a separate journal (it previously appeared within JACS), which later became the Chemical Abstracts Service, a division of ACS that provides chemical information to researchers and others worldwide.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] *Chemical & Engineering News* is a weekly trade magazine that has been published by ACS since 1923.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The society adopted a new constitution aimed at nationalizing the organization in 1890.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] In 1905, the American Chemical Society moved from New York City to Washington, D.C.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] ACS was reincorporated under a congressional charter in 1937.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] Congress and signed by president Franklin D.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] ACS's headquarters moved to its current location in downtown Washington in 1941.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] ACS first established technical divisions in 1908 to foster the exchange of information among scientists who work in particular fields of chemistry or professional interests.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] Divisional activities include organizing technical sessions at ACS meetings, publishing books and resources, administering awards and lectureships, and conducting other events.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The original five divisions were 1) organic chemistry, 2) industrial chemists and chemical engineers, 3) agricultural and food chemistry, 4) fertilizer chemistry, and 5) physical and inorganic chemistry.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] As of 2016, there are 32 technical divisions of ACS.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] This is the largest division of the Society.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] It marked its 100th anniversary in 2008.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The first Chair of the Division was Edward Curtis Franklin.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The Organic Division played a part in establishing Organic Syntheses, Inc. and Organic Reactions, Inc. and it maintains close ties to both organizations.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The symposia also honor national award winners, including the Arthur C.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] Cope Award, Cope Scholar Award, James Flack Norris Award in Physical Organic Chemistry, Herbert C.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] Brown Award for Creative Research in Synthetic Methods.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The Division helps to organize symposia at the international meeting called Pacifichem and it organizes the biennial National Organic Chemistry Symposium (NOS) which highlights recent advances in organic chemistry and hosts the Roger Adams Award address.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The Division also organizes corporate sponsorships to provide fellowships for PhD students and undergraduates.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] It also organizes the Graduate Research Symposium and manages award and travel grant programs for undergraduates.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] Local sections were authorized in 1890 and are autonomous units of the American Chemical Society.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] They elect their own officers and select representatives to the national ACS organization.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] Local sections also provide professional development opportunities for members, organize community outreach events, offer awards, and conduct other business.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The Rhode Island Section was the first local section of ACS, organized in 1891.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] There are currently 186 local sections of the American Chemical Society in all 50 states, the District of Columbia, and Puerto Rico.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] International Chemical Sciences Chapters allow ACS members outside of the U.S. to organize locally for professional and scientific exchange.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] There are currently 36 International Chemical Sciences Chapters.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] ACS states that it offers teacher training to support the professional development of science teachers so they can better present chemistry in the classroom, foster the scientific curiosity of our nation's youth and encourage future generations to pursue scientific careers.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] As of 2009, Clifford and Kathryn Hach donated $33 million to ACS, to continue the work of the Hach Scientific Foundation in supporting high school chemistry teaching.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The Society sponsors the United States National Chemistry Olympiad (USNCO), a contest used to select the four-member team that represents the United States at the International Chemistry Olympiad (IChO).
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The ACS Division of Chemical Education provides standardized tests for various subfields of chemistry.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The two most commonly used tests are the undergraduate-level tests for general and organic chemistry.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] Each of these tests consists of 70 multiple-choice questions, and gives students 110 minutes to complete the exam.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The ACS also approves certified undergraduate programs in chemistry.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] A student who completes the required laboratory and course work—sometimes in excess of what a particular college may require for its Bachelor's degree—is considered by the Society to be well trained for professional work.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The ACS coordinates two annual public awareness campaigns, National Chemistry Week and Chemists Celebrate Earth Week, as part of its educational outreach.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] Since 1978 and 2003 respectively, the campaigns have been celebrated with a yearly theme, such as "Chemistry Colors Our World" (2015) and "Energy: Now and Forever!" (2013).
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The GCI was founded in 1997 as an independent non-profit organization, by chemists Joe Breen and Dennis Hjeresen in cooperation with the Environmental Protection Agency.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The Petroleum Research Fund (PRF) is an endowment fund administered by the ACS that supports advanced education and fundamental research in the petroleum and fossil fuel fields at non-profit institutions.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] Several categories of grants are offered for various career levels and institutions.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The fund awarded more than $25 million in grants in 2007.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The PRF traces its origins to the acquisition of the Universal Oil Products laboratory by a consortium of oil companies in 1931.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The companies established a trust fund, The Petroleum Research Fund, in 1944 to prevent antitrust litigation tied to their UOP assets.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The ACS was named the beneficiary of the trust.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The first grants from the PRF were awarded in 1954.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] In 2000, the trust was transferred to the ACS.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The ACS established The American Chemical Society Petroleum Research Fund and the previous trust was dissolved.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The PRF trust was valued at $144.7 million in December 2014.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The ACS International Activities is the birthplace of the ACS International Center, an online resource for scientists and engineers looking to study abroad or explore an international career or internship.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The site houses information on hundreds of scholarships and grants related to all levels of experience to promote scientific mobility of researchers and practitioners in STEM fields.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The Society grants membership to undergraduates as student members provided they can pay the $25 yearly dues.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] Any university may start its own ACS Student Chapter and receive benefits of undergraduate participation in regional conferences and discounts on ACS publications.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The American Chemical Society administers 64 national awards, medals and prizes based on scientific contributions at various career levels that promote achievement across the chemical sciences.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The ACS national awards program began in 1922 with the establishment of the Priestley Medal, the highest award offered by the ACS, which is given for distinguished services to chemistry.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] Additional awards are offered by divisions, local sections and other bodies of ACS.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] Nichols Medal Award was the first ACS award to honor outstanding researchers in the field of chemistry.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] It was established in 1903 by the ACS New York Section and is named for William H.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] Nichols, an American chemist and businessman and one of the original founders of ACS.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] Of the over 100 Nichols Medalists, 16 have subsequently been awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The Willard Gibbs Award, granted by the ACS Chicago Section, was established in 1910 in honor of Josiah Willard Gibbs, the Yale University professor who formulated the phase rule.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The Georgia Local Section of ACS has awarded the Herty Medal since 1933 recognizing outstanding chemists who have significantly contributed to their chosen fields.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] All chemists in academic, government, or industrial laboratories who have been residing in the southeastern United States for at least 10 years are eligible.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The New York Section of ACS also gives Leadership Awards.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The Leadership Awards are the highest honors given by the Chemical Marketing and Economic Group of ACS NY since December 6, 2012.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] They are presented to leaders of industry, investments, and other sectors, for their contributions to science, technology, engineering and mathematics (STEM) initiatives.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] Roy Vagelos (Regeneron, Merck), Thomas M.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] Connelly (DuPont) and Juan Pablo del Valle (Mexichem).
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The ACS also administers regional awards presented annually at regional meetings.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] Ann Nalley Regional Award for Volunteer Service to the American Chemical Society, Regional Awards for Excellence in High School Teaching, and the Stanley C.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] Israel Regional Award for Advancing Diversity in the Chemical Sciences.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] ACS Publications is the publishing division of the ACS.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] It is a nonprofit academic publisher of scientific journals covering various fields of chemistry and related sciences.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] In addition to academic journals, ACS Publications also publishes *Chemical & Engineering News*, a weekly trade magazine covering news in the chemical profession, *inChemistry*, a magazine for undergraduate students, and *ChemMatters*, a magazine for high school students and teachers.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] However it has recently launched new open access journals and provided authors with open access publishing options.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] In 2006, Congress debated legislation that would have instructed the National Institutes of Health (NIH) to require all investigators it funded to submit copies of final, peer-reviewed journal articles to PubMed Central, a free-access digital repository it operates, within 12 months of publication.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] At the time the American Association of Publishers (of which ACS is a member) hired a public relations firm to counter the open access movement.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] In spite of publishers' opposition, the PubMed Central legislation was passed in December 2007 and became effective in 2008.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] As the open access issue has continued to evolve, so too has the ACS's position.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The ACS has also introduced several open access publishing options for its journals, including providing authors the option to pay an upfront fee to enable free online access to their articles.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] In 2015, the ACS launched the first fully open access journal in the society's history, *ACS Central Science*.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The ACS states that the journal offers the same peer-review standards as its subscription journals, but without publishing charges to either authors or readers.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] A second open access title, *ACS Omega*, an interdisciplinary mega journal, launched in 2016.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] In 2005, the ACS was criticized for opposing the creation of PubChem, which is an open access chemical database developed by the NIH's National Center for Biotechnology Information.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The ACS raised concerns that the publicly supported PubChem database would duplicate and unfairly compete with their existing fee-based Chemical Abstracts Service and argued that the database should only present data created by the Molecular Libraries Screening Center initiative of the NIH.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The ACS lobbied members of the United States Congress to rein in PubChem and hired outside lobbying firms to try to persuade congressional members, the NIH, and the Office of Management and Budget (OMB) against establishing a publicly funded database.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The ACS was unsuccessful, and as of 2012 PubChem is the world's largest free chemical database.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The ACS is also the only provider of a major scientific publication database (SciFinder) that imposes a restriction on the number of records that can be exported.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] None of the competing products, such as Web of Science (owned by Clarivate), Scopus (owned by Elsevier) and The Lens (owned by Cambia) have similar restrictions.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The ACS has been involved in numerous lawsuits regarding access to its databases, trademark rights, and copyrighted material.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] In many of these cases, the ACS lost or ended up with an unenforceable judgement.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The ACS was also found guilty in several lawsuits brought against the Society by its employees.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] In 2004, a group of ACS members criticized the compensation of former executive director and chief executive officer John Crum, whose total salary, expenses, and bonuses for 2002 was reported to be $767,834.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] The ACS defended the figure, saying that it was in line with that of comparable organizations, including for-profit publishers.
[src:olsen-cycle/american-chemical-society] As of 2016, two employees were reported to have a total compensation exceeding $900,000, while 694 had a compensation exceeding $100,000.
[src:olsen-cycle/applied-thermal-engineering] According to the *Journal Citation Reports*, the journal has a 2021 impact factor of 6.9.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] In electromagnetism, **displacement current density** is the rate of change of the electric displacement field **D**, appearing as ∂**D**/∂*t* in Maxwell's equations.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] Displacement current density has the same units as electric current density, and it is a source of the magnetic field just as actual current is.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] However it is not an electric current of moving charges, but a time-varying electric field.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] In physical materials (as opposed to vacuum), there is also a contribution from the slight motion of charges bound in atoms, called dielectric polarization.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] The idea was conceived by James Clerk Maxwell in his 1861 paper "On Physical Lines of Force" (Part III) in connection with the displacement of electric particles in a dielectric medium.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] Maxwell added displacement current to the electric current term in Ampère's circuital law.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] In his 1865 paper A Dynamical Theory of the Electromagnetic Field Maxwell used this amended version of Ampère's circuital law to derive the electromagnetic wave equation.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] This derivation is now generally accepted as a historical landmark in physics by virtue of uniting electricity, magnetism and optics into one single unified theory.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] The displacement current term is now seen as a crucial addition that completed Maxwell's equations and is necessary to explain many phenomena, most particularly the existence of electromagnetic waves.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] The first term on the right hand side is present in material media and in free space.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] It doesn't necessarily come from any actual movement of charge, but it does have an associated magnetic field, just as a current does due to charge motion.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] Some authors apply the name *displacement current* to the first term by itself.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] The second term on the right hand side, called polarization current density, comes from the change in polarization of the individual molecules of the dielectric material.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] Polarization results when, under the influence of an applied electric field, the charges in molecules have moved from a position of exact cancellation.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] The positive and negative charges in molecules separate, causing an increase in the state of polarization **P**.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] A changing state of polarization corresponds to charge movement and so is equivalent to a current, hence the term "polarization current".
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] This polarization is the displacement current as it was originally conceived by Maxwell.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] Maxwell made no special treatment of the vacuum, treating it as a material medium.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] For Maxwell, the effect of **P** was simply to change the relative permittivity *ε*r in the relation **D** = *ε*0*ε*r **E**.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] The modern justification of displacement current is explained below.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] In the equation above, the use of ε accounts for the polarization (if any) of the dielectric material.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] The forms in terms of scalar ε are correct only for linear isotropic materials.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] For linear non-isotropic materials, ε becomes a matrix; even more generally, ε may be replaced by a tensor, which may depend upon the electric field itself, or may exhibit frequency dependence (hence dispersion).
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] where *χ*e is known as the *susceptibility* of the dielectric to electric fields.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] Some implications of the displacement current follow, which agree with experimental observation, and with the requirements of logical consistency for the theory of electromagnetism.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] An example illustrating the need for the displacement current arises in connection with capacitors with no medium between the plates.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] Consider the charging capacitor in the figure.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] The capacitor is in a circuit that causes equal and opposite charges to appear on the left plate and the right plate, charging the capacitor and increasing the electric field between its plates.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] No actual charge is transported through the vacuum between its plates.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] Nonetheless, a magnetic field exists between the plates as though a current were present there as well.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] which extends the notion of current beyond a mere transport of charge.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] Next, this displacement current is related to the charging of the capacitor.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] Consider the current in the imaginary cylindrical surface shown surrounding the left plate.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] A current, say I, passes outward through the left surface L of the cylinder, but no conduction current (no transport of real charges) crosses the right surface R.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] Notice that the electric field **E** between the plates increases as the capacitor charges.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] where S refers to the imaginary cylindrical surface.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] where the first term has a negative sign because charge leaves surface L (the charge is decreasing), the last term has a positive sign because unit vector of surface R is from left to right while the direction of electric field is from right to left, S is the area of the surface R.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] The electric field at surface L is zero because surface L is in the outside of the capacitor.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] where **I** is the current leaving the cylindrical surface (which must equal **I**D) and **J**D is the flow of charge per unit area into the cylindrical surface through the face R.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] As depicted in the figure to the right, the current crossing surface *S*1 is entirely conduction current.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] However, the current crossing surface *S*2 is entirely displacement current.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] Any surface *S*1 that intersects the wire has current I passing through it so Ampère's law gives the correct magnetic field.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] However a second surface *S*2 bounded by the same edge ⁠ $\partial S$ ⁠ could be drawn passing between the capacitor plates, therefore having no current passing through it.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] Without the displacement current term Ampere's law would give zero magnetic field for this surface.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] Therefore, without the displacement current term Ampere's law gives inconsistent results, the magnetic field would depend on the surface chosen for integration.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] Thus the displacement current term ⁠ $\varepsilon _{0}\partial \mathbf {E} /\partial t$ ⁠ is necessary as a second source term which gives the correct magnetic field when the surface of integration passes between the capacitor plates.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] Because the current is increasing the charge on the capacitor's plates, the electric field between the plates is increasing, and the rate of change of electric field gives the correct value for the field **B** found above.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] In a more mathematical vein, the same results can be obtained from the underlying differential equations.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] Consider for simplicity a non-magnetic medium where the relative magnetic permeability is unity, and the complication of magnetization current (bound current) is absent, so that $\mathbf {M} =0$ and $\mathbf {J} =\mathbf {J} _{\mathrm {f} }$ .
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] The current leaving a volume must equal the rate of decrease of charge in a volume.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] where the left side is the divergence of the free current density and the right side is the rate of decrease of the free charge density.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] which implies that the divergence of the current term vanishes, contradicting the continuity equation.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] The added displacement current also leads to wave propagation by taking the curl of the equation for magnetic field.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] and the fact that the divergence of the magnetic field is zero.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] where φ is the electric potential (which can be chosen to satisfy Poisson's equation) and **A** is a vector potential (i.e. magnetic vector potential, not to be confused with surface area, as **A** is denoted elsewhere).
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] The ∇*φ* component on the right hand side is the Gauss's law component, and this is the component that is relevant to the conservation of charge argument above.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] The second term on the right-hand side is the one relevant to the electromagnetic wave equation, because it is the term that contributes to the curl of **E**.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] Because of the vector identity that says the curl of a gradient is zero, ∇*φ* does not contribute to ∇×**E**.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] Maxwell's displacement current was postulated in part III of his 1861 paper 'On Physical Lines of Force'.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] Few topics in modern physics have caused as much confusion and misunderstanding as that of displacement current.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] This is in part due to the fact that Maxwell used a sea of molecular vortices in his derivation, while modern textbooks operate on the basis that displacement current can exist in free space.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] Maxwell's derivation is unrelated to the modern day derivation for displacement current in the vacuum, which is based on consistency between Ampère's circuital law for the magnetic field and the continuity equation for electric charge.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] Maxwell's purpose is stated by him at (Part I, p.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] Clearly Maxwell was driving at magnetization even though the same introduction clearly talks about dielectric polarization.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] Maxwell compared the speed of electricity measured by Wilhelm Eduard Weber and Rudolf Kohlrausch (193,088 miles/second) and the speed of light determined by the Fizeau experiment (195,647 miles/second).
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] — *On Physical Lines of Force*, Part III, *The theory of molecular vortices applied to statical electricity*, pp.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] Maxwell's emphasis on polarization diverted attention towards the electric capacitor circuit, and led to the common belief that Maxwell conceived of displacement current so as to maintain conservation of charge in an electric capacitor circuit.
[src:olsen-cycle/displacement-current] There are a variety of debatable notions about Maxwell's thinking, ranging from his supposed desire to perfect the symmetry of the field equations to the desire to achieve compatibility with the continuity equation.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] An **electric field** (sometimes called **E-field**) is a physical field that surrounds electrically charged particles such as electrons.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] In classical electromagnetism, the electric field of a single charge (or group of charges) describes their capacity to exert attractive or repulsive forces on another charged object.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Charged particles exert attractive forces on each other when the sign of their charges are opposite, one being positive while the other is negative, and repel each other when the signs of the charges are the same.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Because these forces are exerted mutually, two charges must be present for the forces to take place.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] These forces are described by Coulomb's law, which says that the greater the magnitude of the charges, the greater the force, and the greater the distance between them, the weaker the force.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Informally, the greater the charge of an object, the stronger its electric field.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Similarly, an electric field is stronger nearer charged objects and weaker further away.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Electric fields originate from electric charges and time-varying electric currents.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Electric fields and magnetic fields are both manifestations of the electromagnetic field.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Electromagnetism is one of the four fundamental interactions of nature.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Electric fields are important in many areas of physics, and are exploited in electrical technology.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] For example, in atomic physics and chemistry, the interaction in the electric field between the atomic nucleus and electrons is the force that holds these particles together in atoms.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Similarly, the interaction in the electric field between atoms is the force responsible for chemical bonding that result in molecules.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] The electric field is defined as a vector field that associates to each point in space the force per unit of charge exerted on an infinitesimal positive test charge at rest at that point.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] The SI unit for the electric field is the volt per meter (V/m), which is equal to the newton per coulomb (N/C).
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] The electric field is defined at each point in space as the force that would be experienced by an infinitesimally small stationary positive test charge at that point divided by the charge.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] The electric field is defined in terms of force, and force is a vector (i.e. having both magnitude and direction), so it follows that an electric field may be described by a vector field.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] The electric field acts between two charges similarly to the way that the gravitational field acts between two masses, as they both obey an inverse-square law with distance.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] This is the basis for Coulomb's law, which states that, for stationary charges, the electric field varies with the source charge and varies inversely with the square of the distance from the source.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] This means that if the source charge were doubled, the electric field would double, and if you move twice as far away from the source, the field at that point would be only one-quarter its original strength.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] The electric field can be visualized with a set of lines whose direction at each point is the same as those of the field, a concept introduced by Michael Faraday, whose term 'lines of force' is still sometimes used.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] This illustration has the useful property that, when drawn so that each line represents the same amount of flux, the strength of the field is proportional to the density of the lines.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Field lines due to stationary charges have several important properties, including that they always originate from positive charges and terminate at negative charges, they enter all good conductors at right angles, and they never cross or close in on themselves.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] The field lines are a representative concept; the field actually permeates all the intervening space between the lines.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] More or fewer lines may be drawn depending on the precision to which it is desired to represent the field.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] The study of electric fields created by stationary charges is called electrostatics.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Faraday's law describes the relationship between a time-varying magnetic field and the electric field.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] One way of stating Faraday's law is that the curl of the electric field is equal to the negative time derivative of the magnetic field.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] In the absence of time-varying magnetic field, the electric field is therefore called conservative (i.e. curl-free).
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] This implies there are two kinds of electric fields: electrostatic fields and fields arising from time-varying magnetic fields.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] While the curl-free nature of the static electric field allows for a simpler treatment using electrostatics, time-varying magnetic fields are generally treated as a component of a unified electromagnetic field.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] The study of magnetic and electric fields that change over time is called electrodynamics.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Electric fields are caused by electric charges, described by Gauss's law, and time varying magnetic fields, described by Faraday's law of induction.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Together, these laws are enough to define the behavior of the electric field.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] However, since the magnetic field is described as a function of electric field, the equations of both fields are coupled and together form Maxwell's equations that describe both fields as a function of charges and currents.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] In the special case of a steady state (stationary charges and currents), the Maxwell-Faraday inductive effect disappears.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Note that $\varepsilon _{0}$ must be replaced with $\varepsilon$ , permittivity, when charges are in non-empty media.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] When the charges $q_{0}$ and $q_{1}$ have the same sign this force is positive, directed away from the other charge, indicating the particles repel each other.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] When the charges have unlike signs the force is negative, indicating the particles attract.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] This is the *electric field* at point $\mathbf {r} _{0}$ due to the point charge $q_{1}$ ; it is a vector-valued function equal to the Coulomb force per unit charge that a positive point charge would experience at the position $\mathbf {r} _{0}$ .
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Since this formula gives the electric field magnitude and direction at any point $\mathbf {r} _{0}$ in space (except at the location of the charge itself, $\mathbf {r} _{1}$ , where it becomes infinite) it defines a vector field.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] From the above formula it can be seen that the electric field due to a point charge is everywhere directed away from the charge if it is positive, and toward the charge if it is negative, and its magnitude decreases with the inverse square of the distance from the charge.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Due to the linearity of Maxwell's equations, electric fields satisfy the superposition principle, which states that the total electric field, at a point, due to a collection of charges is equal to the vector sum of the electric fields at that point due to the individual charges.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] This principle is useful in calculating the field created by multiple point charges.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] The superposition principle allows for the calculation of the electric field due to a distribution of charge density $\rho (\mathbf {r} )$ .
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] If a system is static, such that magnetic fields are not time-varying, then by Faraday's law, the electric field is curl-free.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] In this case, one can define an electric potential, that is, a function $\varphi$ such that $\mathbf {E} =-\nabla \varphi$ .
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] This is analogous to the gravitational potential.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] The difference between the electric potential at two points in space is called the potential difference (or voltage) between the two points.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] In general, however, the electric field cannot be described independently of the magnetic field.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Faraday's law of induction can be recovered by taking the curl of that equation $\nabla \times \mathbf {E} =-{\frac {\partial (\nabla \times \mathbf {A} )}{\partial t}}=-{\frac {\partial \mathbf {B} }{\partial t}},$ which justifies, a posteriori, the previous form for **E**.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] The equations of electromagnetism are best described in a continuous description.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] However, charges are sometimes best described as discrete points; for example, some models may describe electrons as point sources where charge density is infinite on an infinitesimal section of space.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] A charge q located at $\mathbf {r} _{0}$ can be described mathematically as a charge density ⁠ $\rho (\mathbf {r} )=q\delta (\mathbf {r} -\mathbf {r} _{0})$ ⁠, where the Dirac delta function (in three dimensions) is used.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Conversely, a charge distribution can be approximated by many small point charges.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Electrostatic fields are electric fields that do not change with time.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Such fields are present when systems of charged matter are stationary, or when electric currents are unchanging.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] In that case, Coulomb's law fully describes the field.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] This suggests similarities between the electric field **E** and the gravitational field **g**, or their associated potentials.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Mass is sometimes called "gravitational charge".
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Electrostatic and gravitational forces both are central, conservative and obey an inverse-square law.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] A uniform field is one in which the electric field is constant at every point.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] It can be approximated by placing two conducting plates parallel to each other and maintaining a voltage (potential difference) between them; it is only an approximation because of boundary effects (near the edge of the planes, the electric field is distorted because the plane does not continue).
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Assuming infinite planes, the magnitude of the electric field *E* is: $E=-{\frac {\Delta V}{d}},$ where Δ*V* is the potential difference between the plates and *d* is the distance separating the plates.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] The negative sign arises as positive charges repel, so a positive charge will experience a force away from the positively charged plate, in the opposite direction to that in which the voltage increases.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] In micro- and nano-applications, for instance in relation to semiconductors, a typical magnitude of an electric field is in the order of 106 V⋅m−1, achieved by applying a voltage of the order of 1 volt between conductors spaced 1 μm apart.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] A convenient way to plot the electric field that works even for complex electric fields is to use field lines.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Here the magnitude and direction of an electric field in a region is represented by a number of non-intersecting curved lines that span the region.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] If plotted correctly, the direction of the electric field at any given point is represented by the direction of nearby lines while the magnitude is represented by the density of the field lines in that region.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] They begin at positive charge (or extend from infinity) and end at negative charge (or extend to infinity).
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Further the number of field lines from a given charge must be proportional to that charge.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Electrostatic fields cannot form closed loops.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] (See the figure for an example of a complex electric field line diagram made for a positive point charge which induces electrical charge on the surfaces of 3 nearby conductors.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Field lines can only approximately represent the electric field in a given region.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] (It takes an infinite number of field lines to represent the electric field perfectly.) Nevertheless, these diagrams are useful at illustrating how the electric field changes over a given region.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Electromagnetic fields are electric and magnetic fields, which may change with time, for instance when charges are in motion.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Both the electric current density and the partial derivative of the electric field with respect to time, contribute to the curl of the magnetic field.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] In addition, the Maxwell–Faraday equation states $\nabla \times \mathbf {E} =-{\frac {\partial \mathbf {B} }{\partial t}}.$ These represent two of Maxwell's four equations and they intricately link the electric and magnetic fields together, resulting in the electromagnetic field.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] The equations represent a set of four coupled multi-dimensional partial differential equations which, when solved for a system, describe the combined behavior of the electromagnetic fields.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] As **E** and **B** fields are coupled, it would be misleading to split this expression into "electric" and "magnetic" contributions.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] In particular, an electrostatic field in any given frame of reference in general transforms into a field with a magnetic component in a relatively moving frame.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Accordingly, decomposing the electromagnetic field into an electric and magnetic component is frame-specific, and similarly for the associated energy.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Since **E** and **P** are defined separately, this equation can be used to define **D**.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] The **E** and **D** fields are related by the permittivity of the material, *ε*.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] For non-linear media, **E** and **D** are not proportional.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Materials can have varying extents of linearity, homogeneity and isotropy.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] The invariance of the form of Maxwell's equations under Lorentz transformation can be used to derive the electric field of a uniformly moving point charge.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] The charge of a particle is considered frame invariant, as supported by experimental evidence.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] However the following equation is only applicable when no acceleration is involved in the particle's history where Coulomb's law can be considered or symmetry arguments can be used for solving Maxwell's equations in a simple manner.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] The above equation reduces to that given by Coulomb's law for non-relativistic speeds of the point charge.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Spherical symmetry is not satisfied due to breaking of symmetry in the problem by specification of direction of velocity for calculation of field.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] To illustrate this, field lines of moving charges are sometimes represented as unequally spaced radial lines which would appear equally spaced in a co-moving reference frame.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Special theory of relativity imposes the principle of locality, that requires cause and effect to be time-like separated events where the causal efficacy does not travel faster than the speed of light.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Maxwell's laws are found to confirm to this view since the general solutions of fields are given in terms of retarded time which indicate that electromagnetic disturbances travel at the speed of light.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Advanced time, which also provides a solution for Maxwell's law are ignored as an unphysical solution.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] For the motion of a charged particle, considering for example the case of a moving particle with the above described electric field coming to an abrupt stop, the electric fields at points far from it do not immediately revert to that classically given for a stationary charge.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] On stopping, the field around the stationary points begin to revert to the expected state and this effect propagates outwards at the speed of light while the electric field lines far away from this will continue to point radially towards an assumed moving charge.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] This virtual particle will never be outside the range of propagation of the disturbance in electromagnetic field, since charged particles are restricted to have speeds slower than that of light, which makes it impossible to construct a Gaussian surface in this region that violates Gauss's law.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Another technical difficulty that supports this is that charged particles travelling faster than or equal to speed of light no longer have a unique retarded time.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Since electric field lines are continuous, an electromagnetic pulse of radiation is generated that connects at the boundary of this disturbance travelling outwards at the speed of light.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] In general, any accelerating point charge radiates electromagnetic waves however, non-radiating acceleration is possible in a systems of charges.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] For arbitrarily moving point charges, propagation of potential fields such as Lorenz gauge fields at the speed of light needs to be accounted for by using Liénard–Wiechert potential.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Since the potentials satisfy Maxwell's equations, the fields derived for point charge also satisfy Maxwell's equations.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] The uniqueness of solution for ${\textstyle {t_{r}}}$ for given t , $\mathbf {r}$ and $r_{s}(t)$ is valid for charged particles moving slower than speed of light.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Electromagnetic radiation of accelerating charges is known to be caused by the acceleration dependent term in the electric field from which relativistic correction for Larmor formula is obtained.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] Since the physical interpretation of this indicates that the electric field at a point is governed by the particle's state at a point of time in the future, it is considered as an unphysical solution and hence neglected.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] However, there have been theories exploring the advanced time solutions of Maxwell's equations, such as Feynman Wheeler absorber theory.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] The above equation, although consistent with that of uniformly moving point charges as well as its non-relativistic limit, are not corrected for quantum-mechanical effects.
[src:olsen-cycle/electric-field] In the absence of external fields, spherical conductors exhibit a uniform charge distribution on the surface and hence have the same electric field as that of uniform spherical surface distribution.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Energy harvesters usually provide a very small amount of power for low-energy electronics.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] While the input fuel to some large-scale energy generation costs resources (oil, coal, etc.), the energy source for energy harvesters is present as ambient background.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] For example, temperature gradients exist from the operation of a combustion engine; in urban areas, there is a large amount of electromagnetic energy in the environment due to radio and television broadcasting.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] One of the first examples of ambient energy being used to produce electricity was the successful use of electromagnetic radiation (EMR) to generate the crystal radio.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The principles of energy harvesting from ambient EMR can be demonstrated with basic components.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Energy harvesting devices converting ambient energy into electrical energy have attracted much interest in both the military and commercial sectors.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Some systems convert motion, such as that of ocean waves, into electricity to be used by oceanographic monitoring sensors for autonomous operation.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Future applications may include high-power output devices (or arrays of such devices) deployed at remote locations to serve as reliable power stations for large systems.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Another application is in wearable electronics, where energy-harvesting devices can power or recharge cell phones, mobile computers, and radio communication equipment.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] All of these devices must be sufficiently robust to endure long-term exposure to hostile environments and have a broad range of dynamic sensitivity to exploit the entire spectrum of wave motions.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] In addition, one of the latest techniques to generate electric power from vibration waves is the utilization of Auxetic Boosters.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] This method falls under the category of piezoelectric-based vibration energy harvesting (PVEH), where the harvested electric energy can be directly used to power wireless sensors, monitoring cameras, and other Internet of Things (IoT) devices.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Energy can also be harvested to power small autonomous sensors such as those developed using MEMS technology.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] These systems are often very small and require little power, but their applications are limited by the reliance on battery power.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Scavenging energy from ambient vibrations, wind, heat, or light could enable smart sensors to function indefinitely.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Typical power densities available from energy harvesting devices are highly dependent upon the specific application (affecting the generator's size) and the design itself of the harvesting generator.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] In general, for motion-powered devices, typical values are a few μW/cm3 for human body-powered applications and hundreds of μW/cm3 for generators powered by machinery.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Most energy-scavenging devices for wearable electronics generate very little power.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] In general, energy can be stored in a capacitor, super capacitor, or battery.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Capacitors are used when the application needs to provide huge energy spikes.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Batteries leak less energy and are therefore used when the device needs to provide a steady flow of energy.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] These aspects of the battery depend on the type that is used.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] A common type of battery that is used for this purpose is the lead acid or lithium-ion battery although older types such as nickel metal hydride are still widely used today.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Compared to batteries, super capacitors have virtually unlimited charge-discharge cycles and can therefore operate forever, enabling a maintenance-free operation in IoT and wireless sensor devices.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Current interest in low-power energy harvesting is for independent sensor networks.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] In these applications, an energy harvesting scheme puts power stored into a capacitor then boosts/regulates it to a second storage capacitor or battery for use in the microprocessor or in the data transmission.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The power is usually used in a sensor application and the data is stored or transmitted, possibly through a wireless method.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] One of the main driving forces behind the search for new energy harvesting devices is the desire to power sensor networks and mobile devices without batteries that run on intermittent computing systems and need external charging or service.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Batteries have several limitations, such as limited lifespan, environmental impact, size, weight, and cost.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Energy harvesting devices can provide an alternative or complementary source of power for applications that require low power consumption, such as remote sensing, wearable electronics, condition monitoring, and wireless sensor networks.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Energy harvesting devices can also extend the battery life or enable batteryless operation of some applications.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Another motivation for energy harvesting is the potential to address the issue of climate change by reducing greenhouse gas emissions and fossil fuel consumption.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Energy harvesting devices can utilize renewable and clean sources of energy that are abundant and ubiquitous in the environment, such as solar, thermal, wind, and kinetic energy.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Energy harvesting devices can also reduce the need for power transmission and distribution systems that cause energy losses and environmental impacts.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Energy harvesting devices can therefore contribute to the development of a more sustainable and resilient energy system.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Recent research in energy harvesting has led to the innovation of devices capable of powering themselves through user interactions.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Notable examples include battery-free game boys and other toys, which showcase the potential of devices powered by the energy generated from user actions, such as pressing buttons or turning knobs.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] These studies highlight how energy harvested from interactions can not only power the devices themselves but also extend their operational autonomy, promoting the use of renewable energy sources and reducing reliance on traditional batteries.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] A possible source of energy comes from ubiquitous radio transmitters.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Historically, either a large collection area or close proximity to the radiating wireless energy source is needed to get useful power levels from this source.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The nantenna is one proposed development which would overcome this limitation by making use of the abundant natural radiation (such as solar radiation).
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] One idea is to deliberately broadcast RF energy to power and collect information from remote devices.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] This is now commonplace in passive radio-frequency identification (RFID) systems, but the Safety and US Federal Communications Commission (and equivalent bodies worldwide) limit the maximum power that can be transmitted this way to civilian use.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] This method has been used to power individual nodes in a wireless sensor network.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Various turbine and non-turbine generator technologies can harvest airflow.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Towered wind turbines and airborne wind energy systems (AWES) harness the flow of air.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Multiple companies are developing these technologies, which can operate in low-light environments, such as HVAC ducts, and can be scaled and optimized for the energy requirements of specific applications.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The flow of blood can also be utilized to power devices.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] For example, a pacemaker developed at the University of Bern, uses blood flow to wind up a spring, which then drives an electrical micro-generator.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Water energy harvesting has seen advancements in design, such as generators with transistor-like architecture, achieving high energy conversion efficiency and power density.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Photovoltaic (PV) energy harvesting wireless technology offers significant advantages over wired or solely battery-powered sensor solutions: virtually inexhaustible sources of power with little or no adverse environmental effects.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Indoor PV harvesting solutions have to date been powered by specially tuned amorphous silicon (aSi)a technology most used in Solar Calculators.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] In recent years new PV technologies have come to the forefront in Energy Harvesting such as Dye-Sensitized Solar Cells (DSSC).
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The dyes absorb light much like chlorophyll does in plants.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Electrons released on impact escape to the layer of TiO2 and from there diffuse, through the electrolyte, as the dye can be tuned to the visible spectrum much higher power can be produced.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] At 200 lux a DSSC can provide over 10 μW per cm2.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The piezoelectric effect converts mechanical strain into electric current or voltage.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] This strain can come from many different sources.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Human motion, low-frequency seismic vibrations, and acoustic noise are everyday examples.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Except in rare instances the piezoelectric effect operates in AC requiring time-varying inputs at mechanical resonance to be efficient.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Most piezoelectric electricity sources produce power on the order of milliwatts, too small for system application, but enough for hand-held devices such as some commercially available self-winding wristwatches.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] One proposal is that they are used for micro-scale devices, such as in a device harvesting micro-hydraulic energy.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] In this device, the flow of pressurized hydraulic fluid drives a reciprocating piston supported by three piezoelectric elements which convert the pressure fluctuations into an alternating current.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] As piezo energy harvesting has been investigated only since the late 1990s, it remains an emerging technology.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Nevertheless, some interesting improvements were made with the self-powered electronic switch at INSA school of engineering, implemented by the spin-off Arveni.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] In 2006, the proof of concept of a battery-less wireless doorbell push button was created, and recently, a product showed that classical wireless wallswitch can be powered by a piezo harvester.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Other industrial applications appeared between 2000 and 2005, to harvest energy from vibration and supply sensors for example, or to harvest energy from shock.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Piezoelectric systems can convert motion from the human body into electrical power.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] DARPA has funded efforts to harness energy from leg and arm motion, shoe impacts, and blood pressure for low level power to implantable or wearable sensors.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The nanobrushes are another example of a piezoelectric energy harvester.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Multiple other nanostructures have been exploited to build an energy-harvesting device, for example, a single crystal PMN-PT nanobelt was fabricated and assembled into a piezoelectric energy harvester in 2016.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Careful design is needed to minimise user discomfort.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] These energy harvesting sources by association affect the body.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The Vibration Energy Scavenging Project is another project that is set up to try to scavenge electrical energy from environmental vibrations and movements.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Microbelt can be used to gather electricity from respiration.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Besides, as the vibration of motion from human comes in three directions, a single piezoelectric cantilever based omni-directional energy harvester is created by using 1:2 internal resonance.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Finally, a millimeter-scale piezoelectric energy harvester has also already been created.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Piezo elements are being embedded in walkways to recover the "people energy" of footsteps.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] They can also be embedded in shoes to recover "walking energy".
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Researchers at MIT developed the first micro-scale piezoelectric energy harvester using thin film PZT in 2005.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Arman Hajati and Sang-Gook Kim invented the Ultra Wide-Bandwidth micro-scale piezoelectric energy harvesting device by exploiting the nonlinear stiffness of a doubly clamped microelectromechanical systems (MEMSs) resonator.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The stretching strain in a doubly clamped beam shows a nonlinear stiffness, which provides a passive feedback and results in amplitude-stiffened Duffing mode resonance.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Typically, piezoelectric cantilevers are adopted for the above-mentioned energy harvesting system.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] One drawback is that the piezoelectric cantilever has gradient strain distribution, i.e., the piezoelectric transducer is not fully utilized.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] To address this issue, triangle shaped and L-shaped cantilever are proposed for uniform strain distribution.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] In 2018, Soochow University researchers reported hybridizing a triboelectric nanogenerator and a silicon solar cell by sharing a mutual electrode.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] This device can collect solar energy *or* convert the mechanical energy of falling raindrops into electricity.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] UK telecom company Orange UK created an energy harvesting T-shirt and boots.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Other companies have also done the same.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Brothers Pierre Curie and Jacques Curie gave the concept of piezoelectric effect in 1880.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Piezoelectric effect converts mechanical strain into voltage or electric current and generates electric energy from motion, weight, vibration and temperature changes as shown in the figure.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Considering piezoelectric effect in thin film lead zirconate titanate $Pb(Zr,Ti)O_{3}$ PZT, microelectromechanical systems (MEMS) power generating device has been developed.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] However, Aqsa further developed beam-structured electrostatic devices that are more difficult to fabricate than PZT MEMS devices versus a similar because general silicon processing involves many more mask steps that do not require PZT film.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Piezoelectric $d_{31}$ type sensors and actuators have a cantilever beam structure that consists of a membrane bottom electrode, film, piezoelectric film, and top electrode.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] More than *(3~5 masks)* mask steps are required for patterning of each layer while have very low induced voltage.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Pyroelectric crystals that have a unique polar axis and have spontaneous polarization, along which the spontaneous polarization exists.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The special polar axis—crystallophysical axis *X3* – coincides with the axes *L6*,*L4*, *L3*, and *L2* of the crystals or lies in the unique straight plane *P (class "m")*.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Consequently, the electric centers of positive and negative charges are displaced of an elementary cell from equilibrium positions, i.e., the spontaneous polarization of the crystal changes.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Therefore, all considered crystals have spontaneous polarization $Ps=P3$ .
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Since piezoelectric effect in pyroelectric crystals arises as a result of changes in their spontaneous polarization under external effects (electric fields, mechanical stresses).
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] As a result of displacement, Aqsa Abbasi introduced change in the components $\Delta P_{s}$ along all three axes $\Delta P_{s}=(\Delta P_{1},\Delta P_{2},\Delta P_{3})$ .
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Suppose that $\Delta P_{s}=(\Delta P_{1},\Delta P_{2},\Delta P_{3})$ is proportional to the mechanical stresses causing in a first approximation, which results $\Delta P_{i}=diklTkl$ where *Tkl* represents the mechanical stress and *dikl* represents the piezoelectric modules.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] PZT thin films have attracted attention for applications such as force sensors, accelerometers, gyroscopes actuators, tunable optics, micro pumps, ferroelectric RAM, display systems and smart roads, when energy sources are limited, energy harvesting plays an important role in the environment.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Smart roads have the potential to play an important role in power generation.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Embedding piezoelectric material in the road can convert pressure exerted by moving vehicles into voltage and current.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Piezoelectric sensors are most useful in smart-road technologies that can be used to create systems that are intelligent and improve productivity in the long run.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Imagine highways that alert motorists of a traffic jam before it forms.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Or bridges that report when they are at risk of collapse, or an electric grid that fixes itself when blackouts hit.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] For many decades, scientists and experts have argued that the best way to fight congestion is intelligent transportation systems, such as roadside sensors to measure traffic and synchronized traffic lights to control the flow of vehicles.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] But the spread of these technologies has been limited by cost.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] There are also some other smart-technology shovel ready projects which could be deployed fairly quickly, but most of the technologies are still at the development stage and might not be practically available for five years or more.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The pyroelectric effect converts a temperature change into electric current or voltage.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] It is analogous to the piezoelectric effect, which is another type of ferroelectric behavior.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Pyroelectricity requires time-varying inputs and suffers from small power outputs in energy harvesting applications due to its low operating frequencies.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] However, one key advantage of pyroelectrics over thermoelectrics is that many pyroelectric materials are stable up to 1200 °C or higher, enabling energy harvesting from high temperature sources and thus increasing thermodynamic efficiency.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] One way to directly convert waste heat into electricity is by executing the Olsen cycle on pyroelectric materials.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The Olsen cycle consists of two isothermal and two isoelectric field processes in the electric displacement-electric field (D-E) diagram.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The principle of the Olsen cycle is to charge a capacitor via cooling under low electric field and to discharge it under heating at higher electric field.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Several pyroelectric converters have been developed to implement the Olsen cycle using conduction, convection, or radiation.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] It has also been established theoretically that pyroelectric conversion based on heat regeneration using an oscillating working fluid and the Olsen cycle can reach Carnot efficiency between a hot and a cold thermal reservoir.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Moreover, recent studies have established polyvinylidene fluoride trifluoroethylene [P(VDF-TrFE)] polymers and lead lanthanum zirconate titanate (PLZT) ceramics as promising pyroelectric materials to use in energy converters due to their large energy densities generated at low temperatures.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Additionally, a pyroelectric scavenging device that does not require time-varying inputs was recently introduced.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The energy-harvesting device uses the edge-depolarizing electric field of a heated pyroelectric to convert heat energy into mechanical energy instead of drawing electric current off two plates attached to the crystal-faces.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] In 1821, Thomas Johann Seebeck discovered that a thermal gradient formed between two dissimilar conductors produces a voltage.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] At the heart of the thermoelectric effect is the fact that a temperature gradient in a conducting material results in heat flow; this results in the diffusion of charge carriers.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The flow of charge carriers between the hot and cold regions in turn creates a voltage difference.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] In 1834, Jean Charles Athanase Peltier discovered that running an electric current through the junction of two dissimilar conductors could, depending on the direction of the current, cause it to act as a heater or cooler.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The heat absorbed or produced is proportional to the current, and the proportionality constant is known as the Peltier coefficient.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Today, due to knowledge of the Seebeck and Peltier effects, thermoelectric materials can be used as heaters, coolers and generators (TEGs).
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Ideal thermoelectric materials have a high Seebeck coefficient, high electrical conductivity, and low thermal conductivity.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Low thermal conductivity is necessary to maintain a high thermal gradient at the junction.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Standard thermoelectric modules manufactured today consist of P- and N-doped bismuth-telluride semiconductors sandwiched between two metallized ceramic plates.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The ceramic plates add rigidity and electrical insulation to the system.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The semiconductors are connected electrically in series and thermally in parallel.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Miniature thermocouples have been developed that convert body heat into electricity and generate 40 μ W at 3 V with a 5-degree temperature gradient, while on the other end of the scale, large thermocouples are used in nuclear RTG batteries.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Practical examples are the finger-heartratemeter by the Holst Centre and the thermogenerators by the Fraunhofer-Gesellschaft.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Thermoelectrics contain no materials that must be replenished.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] One downside to thermoelectric energy conversion is low efficiency (currently less than 10%).
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The development of materials that are able to operate in higher temperature gradients, and that can conduct electricity well without also conducting heat (something that was until recently thought impossible ), will result in increased efficiency.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Future work in thermoelectrics could be to convert wasted heat, such as in automobile engine combustion, into electricity.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] This type of harvesting is based on the changing capacitance of vibration-dependent capacitors.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Vibrations separate the plates of a charged variable capacitor, and mechanical energy is converted into electrical energy.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Electrostatic energy harvesters need a polarization source to work and to convert mechanical energy from vibrations into electricity.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The polarization source should be in the order of some hundreds of volts; this greatly complicates the power management circuit.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Another solution consists in using electrets, that are electrically charged dielectrics able to keep the polarization on the capacitor for years.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] It's possible to adapt structures from classical electrostatic induction generators, which also extract energy from variable capacitances, for this purpose.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The resulting devices are self-biasing, and can directly charge batteries, or can produce exponentially growing voltages on storage capacitors, from which energy can be periodically extracted by DC/DC converters.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Magnetic induction refers to the production of an electromotive force (i.e., voltage) in a changing magnetic field.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] This changing magnetic field can be created by motion, either rotation (i.e.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Wiegand effect and Wiegand sensors) or linear movement (i.e. vibration).
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Magnets wobbling on a cantilever are sensitive to even small vibrations and generate microcurrents by moving relative to conductors due to Faraday's law of induction.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] By developing a miniature device of this kind in 2007, a team from the University of Southampton made possible the planting of such a device in environments that preclude having any electrical connection to the outside world.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Sensors in inaccessible places can now generate their own power and transmit data to outside receivers.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] One of the major limitations of the magnetic vibration energy harvester developed at University of Southampton is the size of the generator, in this case approximately one cubic centimeter, which is much too large to integrate into today's mobile technologies.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The complete generator including circuitry is a massive 4 cm by 4 cm by 1 cm nearly the same size as some mobile devices such as the iPod nano.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Further reductions in the dimensions are possible through the integration of new and more flexible materials as the cantilever beam component.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] In 2012, a group at Northwestern University developed a vibration-powered generator out of polymer in the form of a spring.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] This device was able to target the same frequencies as the University of Southampton groups silicon based device but with one third the size of the beam component.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] A new approach to magnetic induction based energy harvesting has also been proposed by using ferrofluids.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The journal article, "Electromagnetic ferrofluid-based energy harvester", discusses the use of ferrofluids to harvest low frequency vibrational energy at 2.2 Hz with a power output of ~80 mW per g.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Quite recently, the change in domain wall pattern with the application of stress has been proposed as a method to harvest energy using magnetic induction.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] In this study, the authors have shown that the applied stress can change the domain pattern in microwires.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Ambient vibrations can cause stress in microwires, which can induce a change in domain pattern and hence change the induction.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Power, of the order of uW/cm2 has been reported.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Commercially successful vibration energy harvesters based on magnetic induction are still relatively few in number.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Examples include products developed by Swedish company ReVibe Energy, a technology spin-out from Saab Group.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Another example is the products developed from the early University of Southampton prototypes by Perpetuum.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] These have to be sufficiently large to generate the power required by wireless sensor nodes (WSN) but in M2M applications this is not normally an issue.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] These harvesters are now being supplied in large volumes to power WSNs made by companies such as GE and Emerson and also for train bearing monitoring systems made by Perpetuum.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Overhead powerline sensors can use magnetic induction to harvest energy directly from the conductor they are monitoring.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Another way of energy harvesting is through the oxidation of blood sugars.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] These energy harvesters are called biobatteries.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] They could be used to power implanted electronic devices (e.g., pacemakers, implanted biosensors for diabetics, implanted active RFID devices, etc.).
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] At present, the Minteer Group of Saint Louis University has created enzymes that could be used to generate power from blood sugars.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] However, the enzymes would still need to be replaced after a few years.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] In 2012, a pacemaker was powered by implantable biofuel cells at Clarkson University under the leadership of Dr.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Tree metabolic energy harvesting is a type of bio-energy harvesting.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Voltree has developed a method for harvesting energy from trees.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] These energy harvesters are being used to power remote sensors and mesh networks as the basis for a long term deployment system to monitor forest fires and weather in the forest.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] According to Voltree's website, the useful life of such a device should be limited only by the lifetime of the tree to which it is attached.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] A small test network was recently deployed in a US National Park forest.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Other sources of energy from trees include capturing the physical movement of the tree in a generator.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Theoretical analysis of this source of energy shows some promise in powering small electronic devices.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] A practical device based on this theory has been built and successfully powered a sensor node for a year.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Soil microbial fuel cells harvest electrical energy from the anaerobic respiration of naturally occurring soil bacteria, which provides the oxidation reaction at the anode.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Soil microbial fuel cells can output microwatts of power, and have been used in both classroom demonstrations and to power analog radar sensors.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] A metamaterial-based device wirelessly converts a 900 MHz microwave signal to 7.3 volts of direct current (greater than that of a USB device).
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The device can be tuned to harvest other signals including Wi-Fi signals, satellite signals, or even sound signals.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The experimental device used a series of five fiberglass and copper conductors.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Conversion efficiency reached 37 percent.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] When traditional antennas are close to each other in space they interfere with each other.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] But since RF power goes down by the cube of the distance, the amount of power is very very small.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] While the claim of 7.3 volts is grand, the measurement is for an open circuit.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Since the power is so low, there can be almost no current when any load is attached.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The pressure of the atmosphere changes naturally over time from temperature changes and weather patterns.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Devices with a sealed chamber can use these pressure differences to extract energy.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] This has been used to provide power for mechanical clocks such as the Atmos clock.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] A relatively new concept of generating energy is to generate energy from oceans.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Large masses of waters are present on the planet which carry with them great amounts of energy.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The energy in this case can be generated by tidal streams, ocean waves, difference in salinity and also difference in temperature.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] As of 2018, efforts are underway to harvest energy this way.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] United States Navy recently was able to generate electricity using difference in temperatures present in the ocean.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] One method to use the temperature difference across different levels of the thermocline in the ocean is by using a thermal energy harvester that is equipped with a material that changes phase while in different temperatures regions.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] This is typically a polymer-based material that can handle reversible heat treatments.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] When the material is changing phase, the energy differential is converted into mechanical energy.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The materials used will need to be able to alter phases, from liquid to solid, depending on the position of the thermocline underwater.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] These phase change materials within thermal energy harvesting units would be an ideal way to recharge or power an unmanned underwater vehicle (UUV) being that it will rely on the warm and cold water already present in large bodies of water; minimizing the need for standard battery recharging.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Capturing this energy would allow for longer-term missions since the need to be collected or return for charging can be eliminated.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] This is also a very environmentally friendly method of powering underwater vehicles.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] There are no emissions that come from utilizing a phase change fluid, and it will likely have a longer lifespan than that of a standard battery.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Electroactive polymers (EAPs) have been proposed for harvesting energy.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] These polymers have a large strain, elastic energy density, and high energy conversion efficiency.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] The total weight of systems based on EAPs (electroactive polymers) is proposed to be significantly lower than those based on piezoelectric materials.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Nanogenerators, such as the one made by Georgia Tech, could provide a new way for powering devices without batteries.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] As of 2008, it only generates some dozen nanowatts, which is too low for any practical application.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Noise has been the subject of a proposal by NiPS Laboratory in Italy to harvest wide spectrum low scale vibrations via a nonlinear dynamical mechanism that can improve harvester efficiency up to a factor 4 compared to traditional linear harvesters.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Asymmetries in bistable energy harvesters can significantly affect dynamic performance and harvested power, especially under nonlinear piezoelectric coupling and parametric variability.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Recent studies show that while asymmetries may degrade response in certain regimes, they can also be exploited—through sloping angle tuning and robust parameter selection—to enhance energy conversion and outperform symmetric designs.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] Combinations of different types of energy harvesters can further reduce dependence on batteries, particularly in environments where the available ambient energy types change periodically.
[src:olsen-cycle/energy-harvesting] This type of complementary balanced energy harvesting has the potential to increase reliability of wireless sensor systems for structural health monitoring.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] The **Ericsson cycle** is named after inventor John Ericsson who designed and built many unique heat engines based on various thermodynamic cycles.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] He is credited with inventing two unique heat engine cycles and developing practical engines based on these cycles.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] His *first* cycle is now known as the closed Brayton cycle, while his second cycle is what is now called the Ericsson cycle.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] Ericsson is one of the few who built open-cycle engines, but he also built closed-cycle ones.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] The ideal Otto and Diesel cycles are not totally reversible because they involve heat transfer through a finite temperature difference during the irreversible isochoric/isobaric heat-addition and isochoric heat-rejection processes.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] The aforementioned irreversibility renders the thermal efficiency of these cycles less than that of a Carnot engine operating within the same limits of temperature.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] Another cycle that features isobaric heat-addition and heat-rejection processes is the Ericsson cycle.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] The Ericsson cycle is an altered version of the Carnot cycle in which the two isentropic processes featured in the Carnot cycle are replaced by two isothermal regeneration processes.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] The Ericsson cycle is often compared with the Stirling cycle, since the engine designs based on these respective cycles are both external combustion engines with regenerators.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] The Ericsson is perhaps most similar to the so-called "double-acting" type of Stirling engine, in which the displacer piston also acts as the power piston.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] Theoretically, both of these cycles have so called *ideal* efficiency, which is the highest allowed by the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] The most well-known ideal cycle is the Carnot cycle, although a useful *Carnot engine* is not known to have been invented.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] The theoretical efficiencies for both, Ericsson and Stirling cycles acting in the same limits are equal to the Carnot Efficiency for same limits.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] The first cycle Ericsson developed is now called the "Brayton cycle", commonly applied to gas turbine engines.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] The second Ericsson cycle is the cycle most commonly referred to as simply the "Ericsson cycle".
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] The (second) Ericsson cycle is also the limit of an ideal gas-turbine Brayton cycle, operating with multistage intercooled compression, and multistage expansion with reheat and regeneration.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] Compared to the Brayton cycle which uses adiabatic compression and expansion, the second Ericsson cycle uses isothermal compression and expansion, thus producing more net work per stroke.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] Also the use of regeneration in the Ericsson cycle increases efficiency by reducing the required heat input.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] For further comparisons of thermodynamic cycles, see heat engine.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] The Ericsson engine is based on the Ericsson cycle, and is known as an "external combustion engine", because it is externally heated.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] To improve efficiency, the engine has a regenerator or recuperator between the compressor and the expander.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] The engine can be run open- or closed-cycle.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] Expansion occurs simultaneously with compression, on opposite sides of the piston.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] Ericsson coined the term "regenerator" for his independent invention of the mixed-flow counter-current heat exchanger.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] Robert Stirling had invented the same device, prior to Ericsson, so the invention is credited to Stirling.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] Stirling called it an "economiser" or "economizer", because it increased the fuel economy of various types of heat processes.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] The invention was found to be useful, in many other devices and systems, where it became more widely used, since other types of engines became favored over the Stirling engine.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] The term "regenerator" is now the name given to the component in the Stirling engine.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] The term "recuperator" refers to a separated-flow, counter-current heat exchanger.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] As if this weren't confusing enough, a mixed-flow regenerator is sometimes used as a quasi-separated-flow recuperator.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] This can be done through the use of moving valves, or by a rotating regenerates with fixed baffles, or by the use of other moving parts.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] When heat is recovered from exhaust gases and used to preheat combustion air, typically the term recuperator is used, because the two flows are separate.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] In 1791, before Ericsson, John Barber proposed a similar engine.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] The Barber engine used a bellows compressor and a turbine expander, but it lacked a regenerator/recuperator.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] There are no records of a working Barber engine.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] Ericsson invented and patented his first engine using an external version of the Brayton cycle in 1833 (number 6409/1833 British).
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] This was 18 years before Joule and 43 years before Brayton.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] Brayton engines were all piston engines and for the most part, internal combustion versions of the un-recuperated Ericsson engine.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] The "Brayton cycle" is now known as the gas turbine cycle, which differs from the original "Brayton cycle" in the use of a turbine compressor and expander.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] The gas turbine cycle is used for all modern gas turbine and turbojet engines, however simple cycle turbines are often recuperated to improve efficiency and these recuperated turbines more closely resemble Ericsson's work.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] Ericsson eventually abandoned the open cycle in favor of the traditional closed Stirling cycle.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] Ericsson's engine can easily be modified to operate in a closed-cycle mode, using a second, lower-pressure, cooled container between the original exhaust and intake.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] In closed cycle, the lower pressure can be significantly above ambient pressure, and He or H2 working gas can be used.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] Because of the higher pressure difference between the upward and downward movement of the work-piston, specific output can be greater than of a valveless Stirling engine.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] Ericsson's engine also minimizes mechanical losses: the power necessary for compression does not go through crank-bearing frictional losses, but is applied directly from the expansion force.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] The piston-type Ericsson engine can potentially be the highest efficiency heat engine arrangement ever constructed.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] Admittedly, this has yet to be proven in practical applications.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] Ericsson designed and built a very great number of engines running on various cycles including steam, Stirling, Brayton, externally heated diesel air fluid cycle.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] He ran his engines on a great variety of fuels including coal and solar heat.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] Ericsson was also responsible for an early use of the screw propeller for ship propulsion, in the USS *Princeton*, built in 1842–43.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] The combination engine produced about 300 horsepower (220 kW).
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] It had a combination of four dual-piston engines; the larger expansion piston/cylinder, at 14 feet (4.3 m) in diameter, was perhaps the largest piston ever built.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] Rumor has it that tables were placed on top of those pistons (obviously in the cool compression chamber, not the hot power chamber) and dinner was served and eaten, while the engine was running at full power.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] At 6.5 RPM the pressure was limited to 8 psi (55 kPa).
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] According to the official report it only consumed 4200 kg coal per 24 hours (original target was 8000 kg, which is still better than contemporary steam engines).
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] The one sea trial proved that even though the engine ran well, the ship was underpowered.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] Some time after the trials, the *Ericsson* sank.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] When it was raised, the Ericsson-cycle engine was removed and a steam engine took its place.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] The ship was wrecked when blown aground in November 1892 at the entrance to Barkley Sound, British Columbia, Canada.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] The Ericsson cycle (and the similar Brayton cycle) receives renewed interest today to extract power from the exhaust heat of gas (and producer gas) engines and solar concentrators.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] An important advantage of the Ericsson cycle over the widely known Stirling engine is often not recognized : the volume of the heat exchanger does not adversely affect the efficiency.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] (...)*despite having significant advantages over the Stirling.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] For medium and large engines the cost of valves can be small compared to this advantage.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] Turbocompressor plus turbine implementations seem favorable in the MWe range, positive displacement compressor plus turbine for Nx100 kWe power, and positive displacement compressor+expander below 100 kW.
[src:olsen-cycle/ericsson-cycle] With high temperature hydraulic fluid, both the compressor and the expander can be liquid-ring pumps even up to 400 °C, with rotating casing for best efficiency.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Hysteresis can be found in physics, chemistry, engineering, biology, and economics.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] It is incorporated in many artificial systems: for example, in thermostats and Schmitt triggers, it prevents unwanted frequent switching.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Hysteresis can be a dynamic lag between an input and an output that disappears if the input is varied more slowly; this is known as *rate-dependent* hysteresis.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] However, phenomena such as the magnetic hysteresis loops are mainly *rate-independent*, which makes a durable memory possible.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Systems with hysteresis are nonlinear, and can be mathematically challenging to model.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Some hysteretic models, such as the Preisach model (originally applied to ferromagnetism) and the Bouc–Wen model, attempt to capture general features of hysteresis; and there are also phenomenological models for particular phenomena such as the Jiles–Atherton model for ferromagnetism.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] It is difficult to define hysteresis precisely.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Mayergoyz wrote "...the very meaning of hysteresis varies from one area to another, from paper to paper and from author to author.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] As a result, a stringent mathematical definition of hysteresis is needed in order to avoid confusion and ambiguity.".
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The term "hysteresis" is derived from ὑστέρησις, an Ancient Greek word meaning "deficiency" or "lagging behind".
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] It was coined in 1881 by Sir James Alfred Ewing to describe the behaviour of magnetic materials.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Some early work on describing hysteresis in mechanical systems was performed by James Clerk Maxwell.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Subsequently, hysteretic models have received significant attention in the works of Ferenc Preisach (Preisach model of hysteresis), Louis Néel and Douglas Hugh Everett in connection with magnetism and absorption.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] A more formal mathematical theory of systems with hysteresis was developed in the 1970s by a group of Russian mathematicians led by Mark Krasnosel'skii.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] One type of hysteresis is a lag between input and output.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] where $\chi _{\text{i}}$ is the instantaneous response and $\Phi _{d}(\tau )$ is the impulse response to an impulse that occurred $\tau$ time units in the past.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] In the frequency domain, input and output are related by a complex *generalized susceptibility* that can be computed from $\Phi _{d}$ ; it is mathematically equivalent to a transfer function in linear filter theory and analogue signal processing.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] This kind of hysteresis is often referred to as *rate-dependent hysteresis*.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] If the input is reduced to zero, the output continues to respond for a finite time.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] This constitutes a memory of the past, but a limited one because it disappears as the output decays to zero.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The phase lag depends on the frequency of the input, and goes to zero as the frequency decreases.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] When rate-dependent hysteresis is due to dissipative effects like friction, it is associated with power loss.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Systems with *rate-independent hysteresis* have a *persistent* memory of the past that remains after the transients have died out.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The future development of such a system depends on the history of states visited, but does not fade as the events recede into the past.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] If an input variable *X(t)* cycles from *X*0 to *X*1 and back again, the output *Y(t)* may be *Y*0 initially but a different value *Y*2 upon return.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The values of *Y(t)* depend on the path of values that *X(t)* passes through but not on the speed at which it traverses the path.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Many authors restrict the term hysteresis to mean only rate-independent hysteresis.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Hysteresis effects can be characterized using the Preisach model and the generalized Prandtl−Ishlinskii model.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] In control systems, hysteresis can be used to filter signals so that the output reacts less rapidly than it otherwise would by taking recent system history into account.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] For example, a thermostat controlling a heater may switch the heater on when the temperature drops below A, but not turn it off until the temperature rises above B.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] (For instance, if one wishes to maintain a temperature of 20 °C then one might set the thermostat to turn the heater on when the temperature drops to below 18 °C and off when the temperature exceeds 22 °C).
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Similarly, a pressure switch can be designed to exhibit hysteresis, with pressure set-points substituted for temperature thresholds.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Often, some amount of hysteresis is intentionally added to an electronic circuit to prevent unwanted rapid switching.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] This and similar techniques are used to compensate for contact bounce in switches, or noise in an electrical signal.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] A Schmitt trigger is a simple electronic circuit that exhibits this property.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] A latching relay uses a solenoid to actuate a ratcheting mechanism that keeps the relay closed even if power to the relay is terminated.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Some positive feedback from the output to one input of a comparator can increase the natural hysteresis (a function of its gain) it exhibits.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Hysteresis is essential to the workings of some memristors (circuit components which "remember" changes in the current passing through them by changing their resistance).
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Hysteresis can be used when connecting arrays of elements such as nanoelectronics, electrochrome cells and memory effect devices using passive matrix addressing.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Shortcuts are made between adjacent components (see crosstalk) and the hysteresis helps to keep the components in a particular state while the other components change states.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Thus, all rows can be addressed at the same time instead of individually.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] In the field of audio electronics, a noise gate often implements hysteresis intentionally to prevent the gate from "chattering" when signals close to its threshold are applied.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] A hysteresis is sometimes intentionally added to computer algorithms.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The field of user interface design has borrowed the term hysteresis to refer to times when the state of the user interface intentionally lags behind the apparent user input.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] For example, a menu that was drawn in response to a mouse-over event may remain on-screen for a brief moment after the mouse has moved out of the trigger region and the menu region.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] This allows the user to move the mouse directly to an item on the menu, even if part of that direct mouse path is outside of both the trigger region and the menu region.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] For instance, right-clicking on the desktop in most Windows interfaces will create a menu that exhibits this behavior.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] In aerodynamics, hysteresis can be observed when decreasing the angle of attack of a wing after stall, regarding the lift and drag coefficients.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The angle of attack at which the flow on top of the wing reattaches is generally lower than the angle of attack at which the flow separates during the increase of the angle of attack.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Hysteresis can be observed in the stage-flow relationship of a river during rapidly changing conditions such as passing of a flood wave.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] It is most pronounced in low gradient streams with steep leading edge hydrographs.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Moving parts within machines, such as the components of a gear train, normally have a small gap between them, to allow movement and lubrication.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] As a consequence of this gap, any reversal in direction of a drive part will not be passed on immediately to the driven part.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] This unwanted delay is normally kept as small as practicable, and is usually called backlash.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The amount of backlash will increase with time as the surfaces of moving parts wear.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] In the elastic hysteresis of rubber, the area in the centre of a hysteresis loop is the energy dissipated due to material internal friction.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Elastic hysteresis was one of the first types of hysteresis to be examined.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The effect can be demonstrated using a rubber band with weights attached to it.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] If the top of a rubber band is hung on a hook and small weights are attached to the bottom of the band one at a time, it will stretch and get longer.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] As more weights are *loaded* onto it, the band will continue to stretch because the force the weights are exerting on the band is increasing.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] When each weight is taken off, or *unloaded*, the band will contract as the force is reduced.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] As the weights are taken off, each weight that produced a specific length as it was loaded onto the band now contracts less, resulting in a slightly longer length as it is unloaded.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] This is because the band does not obey Hooke's law perfectly.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The hysteresis loop of an idealized rubber band is shown in the figure.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] In terms of force, the rubber band was harder to stretch when it was being loaded than when it was being unloaded.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] In terms of time, when the band is unloaded, the effect (the length) lagged behind the cause (the force of the weights) because the length has not yet reached the value it had for the same weight during the loading part of the cycle.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] In terms of energy, more energy was required during the loading than the unloading, the excess energy being dissipated as thermal energy.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Elastic hysteresis is more pronounced when the loading and unloading is done quickly than when it is done slowly.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Some materials such as hard metals don't show elastic hysteresis under a moderate load, whereas other hard materials like granite and marble do.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Materials such as rubber exhibit a high degree of elastic hysteresis.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] When the intrinsic hysteresis of rubber is being measured, the material can be considered to behave like a gas.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] When a rubber band is stretched, it heats up, and if it is suddenly released, it cools down perceptibly.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] These effects correspond to a large hysteresis from the thermal exchange with the environment and a smaller hysteresis due to internal friction within the rubber.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] This proper, intrinsic hysteresis can be measured only if the rubber band is thermally isolated.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Small vehicle suspensions using rubber (or other elastomers) can achieve the dual function of springing and damping because rubber, unlike metal springs, has pronounced hysteresis and does not return all the absorbed compression energy on the rebound.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Mountain bikes have made use of elastomer suspension, as did the original Mini car.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The primary cause of rolling resistance when a body (such as a ball, tire, or wheel) rolls on a surface is hysteresis.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] This is attributed to the viscoelastic characteristics of the material of the rolling body.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The contact angle formed between a liquid and solid phase will exhibit a range of contact angles that are possible.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] There are two common methods for measuring this range of contact angles.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The first method is referred to as the tilting base method.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Once a drop is dispensed on the surface with the surface level, the surface is then tilted from 0° to 90°.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] As the drop is tilted, the downhill side will be in a state of imminent wetting while the uphill side will be in a state of imminent dewetting.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] As the tilt increases the downhill contact angle will increase and represents the advancing contact angle while the uphill side will decrease; this is the receding contact angle.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The values for these angles just prior to the drop releasing will typically represent the advancing and receding contact angles.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The difference between these two angles is the contact angle hysteresis.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The second method is often referred to as the add/remove volume method.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] When the maximum liquid volume is removed from the drop without the interfacial area decreasing the receding contact angle is thus measured.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] When volume is added to the maximum before the interfacial area increases, this is the advancing contact angle.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] As with the tilt method, the difference between the advancing and receding contact angles is the contact angle hysteresis.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Most researchers prefer the tilt method; the add/remove method requires that a tip or needle stay embedded in the drop which can affect the accuracy of the values, especially the receding contact angle.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The bubble shape hysteresis is a consequence of gas compressibility, which causes the bubbles to behave differently across expansion and contraction.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] During expansion, bubbles undergo large non equilibrium jumps in volume, while during contraction the bubbles are more stable and undergo a relatively smaller jump in volume resulting in an asymmetry across expansion and contraction.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The bubble shape hysteresis is qualitatively similar to the adsorption hysteresis, and as in the contact angle hysteresis, the interfacial properties play an important role in bubble shape hysteresis.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The existence of the bubble shape hysteresis has important consequences in interfacial rheology experiments involving bubbles.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] As a result of the hysteresis, not all sizes of the bubbles can be formed on a capillary.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Further the gas compressibility causing the hysteresis leads to unintended complications in the phase relation between the applied changes in interfacial area to the expected interfacial stresses.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] These difficulties can be avoided by designing experimental systems to avoid the bubble shape hysteresis.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Hysteresis can also occur during physical adsorption processes.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] In this type of hysteresis, the quantity adsorbed is different when gas is being added than it is when being removed.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The specific causes of adsorption hysteresis are still an active area of research, but it is linked to differences in the nucleation and evaporation mechanisms inside mesopores.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] These mechanisms are further complicated by effects such as cavitation and pore blocking.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] In physical adsorption, hysteresis is evidence of mesoporosity-indeed, the definition of mesopores (2–50 nm) is associated with the appearance (50 nm) and disappearance (2 nm) of mesoporosity in nitrogen adsorption isotherms as a function of Kelvin radius.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] An adsorption isotherm showing hysteresis is said to be of Type IV (for a wetting adsorbate) or Type V (for a non-wetting adsorbate), and hysteresis loops themselves are classified according to how symmetric the loop is.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Adsorption hysteresis loops also have the unusual property that it is possible to scan within a hysteresis loop by reversing the direction of adsorption while on a point on the loop.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The resulting scans are called "crossing", "converging", or "returning", depending on the shape of the isotherm at this point.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The relationship between matric water potential and water content is the basis of the water retention curve.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Matric potential measurements (Ψm) are converted to volumetric water content (θ) measurements based on a site or soil specific calibration curve.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Hysteresis is a source of water content measurement error.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Matric potential hysteresis arises from differences in wetting behaviour causing dry medium to re-wet; that is, it depends on the saturation history of the porous medium.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Hysteretic behaviour means that, for example, at a matric potential (Ψm) of 5 kPa, the volumetric water content (θ) of a fine sandy soil matrix could be anything between 8% and 25%.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Tensiometers are directly influenced by this type of hysteresis.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Two other types of sensors used to measure soil water matric potential are also influenced by hysteresis effects within the sensor itself.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Resistance blocks, both nylon and gypsum based, measure matric potential as a function of electrical resistance.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The relation between the sensor's electrical resistance and sensor matric potential is hysteretic.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Thermocouples measure matric potential as a function of heat dissipation.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Hysteresis occurs because measured heat dissipation depends on sensor water content, and the sensor water content–matric potential relationship is hysteretic.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] As of 2002, only desorption curves are usually measured during calibration of soil moisture sensors.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Despite the fact that it can be a source of significant error, the sensor specific effect of hysteresis is generally ignored.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] When an external magnetic field is applied to a ferromagnetic material such as iron, the atomic domains align themselves with it.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Even when the field is removed, part of the alignment will be retained: the material has become *magnetized*.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Once magnetized, the magnet will stay magnetized indefinitely.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] To demagnetize it requires heat or a magnetic field in the opposite direction.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] This is the effect that provides the element of memory in a hard disk drive.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The relationship between field strength *H* and magnetization *M* is not linear in such materials.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] If a magnet is demagnetized (*H = M = 0*) and the relationship between *H* and *M* is plotted for increasing levels of field strength, *M* follows the *initial magnetization curve*.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] This curve increases rapidly at first and then approaches an asymptote called magnetic saturation.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] If the magnetic field is now reduced monotonically, *M* follows a different curve.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] At zero field strength, the magnetization is offset from the origin by an amount called the remanence.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] If the *H-M* relationship is plotted for all strengths of applied magnetic field the result is a hysteresis loop called the *main loop*.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The width of the middle section is twice the coercivity of the material.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] A closer look at a magnetization curve generally reveals a series of small, random jumps in magnetization called Barkhausen jumps.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] This effect is due to crystallographic defects such as dislocations.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Magnetic hysteresis loops are not exclusive to materials with ferromagnetic ordering.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Other magnetic orderings, such as spin glass ordering, also exhibit this phenomenon.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The phenomenon of hysteresis in ferromagnetic materials is the result of two effects: rotation of magnetization and changes in size or number of magnetic domains.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] In general, the magnetization varies (in direction but not magnitude) across a magnet, but in sufficiently small magnets, it does not.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] In these single-domain magnets, the magnetization responds to a magnetic field by rotating.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Single-domain magnets are used wherever a strong, stable magnetization is needed (for example, magnetic recording).
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Larger magnets are divided into regions called *domains*.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Across each domain, the magnetization does not vary; but between domains are relatively thin *domain walls* in which the direction of magnetization rotates from the direction of one domain to another.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] If the magnetic field changes, the walls move, changing the relative sizes of the domains.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Because the domains are not magnetized in the same direction, the magnetic moment per unit volume is smaller than it would be in a single-domain magnet; but domain walls involve rotation of only a small part of the magnetization, so it is much easier to change the magnetic moment.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The magnetization can also change by addition or subtraction of domains (called *nucleation* and *denucleation*).
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The most known empirical models in hysteresis are Preisach and Jiles-Atherton models.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] These models allow an accurate modeling of the hysteresis loop and are widely used in the industry.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] However, these models lose the connection with thermodynamics and the energy consistency is not ensured.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] A more recent model, with a more consistent thermodynamical foundation, is the vectorial incremental nonconservative consistent hysteresis (VINCH) model of Lavet et al.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] There are a great variety of applications of the hysteresis in ferromagnets.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Many of these make use of their ability to retain a memory, for example magnetic tape, hard disks, and credit cards.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] In these applications, *hard* magnets (high coercivity) like iron are desirable, such that as much energy is absorbed as possible during the write operation and the resultant magnetized information is not easily erased.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] On the other hand, magnetically *soft* (low coercivity) iron is used for the cores in electromagnets.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The low coercivity minimizes the energy loss associated with hysteresis, as the magnetic field periodically reverses in the presence of an alternating current.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The low energy loss during a hysteresis loop is the reason why soft iron is used for transformer cores and electric motors.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Electrical hysteresis typically occurs in ferroelectric material, where domains of polarization contribute to the total polarization.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Polarization is the electrical dipole moment (either C·m−2 or C·m).
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The mechanism, an organization of the polarization into domains, is similar to that of magnetic hysteresis.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Hysteresis manifests itself in state transitions when melting temperature and freezing temperature do not agree.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] For example, agar melts at 85 °C (185 °F) and solidifies from 32 to 40 °C (90 to 104 °F).
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] This is to say that once agar is melted at 85 °C, it retains a liquid state until cooled to 40 °C.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Therefore, from the temperatures of 40 to 85 °C, agar can be either solid or liquid, depending on which state it was before.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Hysteresis in cell biology often follows bistable systems where the same input state can lead to two different, stable outputs.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Where bistability can lead to digital, switch-like outputs from the continuous inputs of chemical concentrations and activities, hysteresis makes these systems more resistant to noise.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] These systems are often characterized by higher values of the input required to switch into a particular state as compared to the input required to stay in the state, allowing for a transition that is not continuously reversible, and thus less susceptible to noise.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] In the case of mitosis, irreversibility is essential to maintain the overall integrity of the system such that we have three designated checkpoints to account for this: G1/S, G2/M, and the spindle checkpoint.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Irreversible hysteresis in this context ensures that once a cell commits to a specific phase (e.g., entering mitosis or DNA replication), it does not revert to a previous phase, even if conditions or regulatory signals change.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Based on the irreversible hysteresis curve, there does exist an input at which the cell jumps to the next stable state, but there is no input that allows the cell to revert to its previous stable state, even when the input is 0, demonstrating irreversibility.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Positive feedback is critical for generating hysteresis in the cell cycle.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] For example: In the G2/M transition, active CDK1 promotes the activation of more CDK1 molecules by inhibiting Wee1 (an inhibitor) and activating Cdc25 (a phosphatase that activates CDK1).
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] These loops lock the cell into its current state and amplify the activation of CDK1.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Positive feedback also serves to create a bistable system where CDK1 is either fully inactivated or fully activated.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Hysteresis prevents the cell from oscillating between these two states from small perturbations in signal (input).
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] A biochemical system that is under the control of reversible hysteresis has both forward and reverse trajectories.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The system generally requires a higher [input] to proceed forward into the next bistable state then to exit from that stage.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] For example, cells undergoing cell division exhibit reversible hysteresis in that it takes a higher concentration of cyclins to switch them from G2 phase into mitosis than to stay in mitosis once begun.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Additionally, because the [cyclin] required to reverse the cell back to the G2 phase is much lower than the [cyclin] to enter mitosis, this improved the bistability of mitosis because it is more resistance to weak or transient signals.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Small perturbations the [input] will be unable to push the cell out of mitosis so easily.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] In systems with bistability, the same input level can correspond to two distinct stable states (e.g., "low output" and "high output").
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The actual state of the system depends on its history –whether the input level was increasing (forward trajectory) or decreasing (backward trajectory).
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Thus, it is difficult to determine which state a cell is in if given only a bistability curve.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The cell's ability to "remember" its prior state ensures stability and prevents it from switching states unnecessarily due to minor fluctuations in input.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] This memory is often maintained through molecular feedback loops, such as positive feedback in signaling pathways, or the persistence of regulatory molecules like proteins or phosphorylated components.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] For example, the refractory period in action potentials is primarily controlled by history.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Absolute refraction period prevents a volted-gated sodium channel from activating or refiring after it has just fired.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] This is because following the absolute refractory period, the neuron is less excitable due to hyperpolarization caused by potassium efflux.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] This molecular inhibitory feedback creates a memory for the neuron or cell, so that the neuron does not fire too soon.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] As time passes, the neuron or cell will slowly lose the memory of having fired and will begin to fire again.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Thus, memory is time-dependent, which is important in maintaining homeostasis and regulating many different biological processes.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Cells advancing through the cell cycle must make an irreversible commitment to mitosis, ensuring they do not revert to interphase before successfully segregating their chromosomes.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] A mathematical model of cell-cycle progression in cell-free egg extracts from frogs suggests that hysteresis in the molecular control system drives these irreversible transitions into and out of mitosis.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Here, Cdc2 (Cyclin-dependent kinase 1 or CDK1) is responsible for mitotic entry and exit such that binding of cyclin B forms a complex called Maturation-Promoting Factor (MPF).
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The activation threshold for mitotic entry was found to be between 32 and 40 nM cyclin B in the frog extracts while the inactivation threshold for exiting mitosis was lower, between 16 and 24 nM cyclin B.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The higher threshold for mitotic entry compared to the lower threshold for mitotic exit indicates hysteresis, a hallmark of history-dependent behavior in the system.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Concentrations between 24 and 32 nM cyclin B demonstrated bistability, where the system could exist in either interphase or mitosis, depending on its prior state (history).
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Though, the cell cycle is not completely irreversible, the difference in thresholds is enough for growth and survival of the cells.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Hysteric thresholds in biological systems are not definite and can be recalibrated.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] For example, unreplicated DNA or chromosomes inhibits Cdc25 phosphatase and maintains Wee1 kinase activity.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] This prevents the activation of Cyclin B-Cdc2, effectively raising the threshold for mitotic entry.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] As a result, the cell delays the transition to mitosis until replication is complete, ensuring genomic integrity.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Other instances may be DNA damage and unattached chromosomes during the spindle assembly checkpoint.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Biochemical systems can also show hysteresis-like output when slowly varying states that are not directly monitored are involved, as in the case of the cell cycle arrest in yeast exposed to mating pheromone.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The proposed model is that α-factor, a yeast mating pheromone binds to its analog receptor on another yeast cell promoting transcription of Fus3 and promoting mating.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Fus3 further promotes Far1 which inhibits Cln1/2, activators of the cell cycle.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] This is representative of a coherent feedforward loop that can modeled as a hysteresis curve.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Far1 transcription is the primary mechanism responsible for the hysteresis observed in cell-cycle reentry.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The history of pheromone exposure influences the accumulation of Far1, which, in turn, determines the delay in cell-cycle reentry.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Previous pulse experiments demonstrated that after exposure to high pheromone concentrations, cells enter a stabilized arrested state where reentry thresholds are elevated due to increased Far1-dependent inhibition of CDK activity.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Even when pheromone levels drop to concentrations that would allow naive cells to reenter the cell cycle, pre-exposed cells take longer to resume proliferation.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] This delay reflects the history-dependent nature of hysteresis, where past exposure to high pheromone concentrations influences the current state.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Hysteresis ensures that cells make robust and irreversible decisions about mating and proliferation in response to pheromone signals.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] It allows cells to "remember" high pheromone exposure, and this helps yeast cells adapt and stability their responses to environmental conditions, avoiding fast premature reentry into the cell cycle, the moment that pheromone signal dies down.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Additionally, the duration of cell cycle arrest depends not only on the final level of input Fus3, but also on the previously achieved Fus3 levels.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Experiments in this type of hysteresis benefit from the ability to change the concentration of the inputs with time.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The mechanisms are often elucidated by allowing independent control of the concentration of the key intermediate, for instance, by using an inducible promoter.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Here, the duration of cell cycle arrest depends not only on the final level of input Fus3, but also on the previously achieved Fus3 levels.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] In developmental biology, cell type diversity is regulated by long range-acting signaling molecules called morphogens that pattern uniform pools of cells in a concentration- and time-dependent manner.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The morphogen sonic hedgehog (Shh), for example, acts on limb bud and neural progenitors to induce expression of a set of homeodomain-containing transcription factors to subdivide these tissues into distinct domains.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] It has been shown that these tissues have a 'memory' of previous exposure to Shh.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] In neural tissue, this hysteresis is regulated by a homeodomain (HD) feedback circuit that amplifies Shh signaling.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] In this circuit, expression of Gli transcription factors, the executors of the Shh pathway, is suppressed.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Glis are processed to repressor forms (GliR) in the absence of Shh, but in the presence of Shh, a proportion of Glis are maintained as full-length proteins allowed to translocate to the nucleus, where they act as activators (GliA) of transcription.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] By reducing Gli expression then, the HD transcription factors reduce the total amount of Gli (GliT), so a higher proportion of GliT can be stabilized as GliA for the same concentration of Shh.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] There is some evidence that T cells exhibit hysteresis in that it takes a lower signal threshold to activate T cells that have been previously activated.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Ras GTPase activation is required for downstream effector functions of activated T cells.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Triggering of the T cell receptor induces high levels of Ras activation, which results in higher levels of GTP-bound (active) Ras at the cell surface.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The property by which some neurons do not return to their basal conditions from a stimulated condition immediately after removal of the stimulus is an example of hysteresis.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Neuropsychology, in exploring the neural correlates of consciousness, interfaces with neuroscience, although the complexity of the central nervous system is a challenge to its study (that is, its operation resists easy reduction).
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Context-dependent memory and state-dependent memory show hysteretic aspects of neurocognition.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Lung hysteresis is evident when observing the compliance of a lung on inspiration versus expiration.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The difference in compliance (Δvolume/Δpressure) is due to the additional energy required to overcome surface tension forces during inspiration to recruit and inflate additional alveoli.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The transpulmonary pressure vs Volume curve of inhalation is different from the Pressure vs Volume curve of exhalation, the difference being described as hysteresis.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Lung volume at any given pressure during inhalation is less than the lung volume at any given pressure during exhalation.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] A hysteresis effect may be observed in voicing onset versus offset.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The threshold value of the subglottal pressure required to start the vocal fold vibration is lower than the threshold value at which the vibration stops, when other parameters are kept constant.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] In utterances of vowel-voiceless consonant-vowel sequences during speech, the intraoral pressure is lower at the voice onset of the second vowel compared to the voice offset of the first vowel, the oral airflow is lower, the transglottal pressure is larger and the glottal width is smaller.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Hysteresis is a commonly encountered phenomenon in ecology and epidemiology, where the observed equilibrium of a system can not be predicted solely based on environmental variables, but also requires knowledge of the system's past history.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Notable examples include the theory of spruce budworm outbreaks and behavioral-effects on disease transmission.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] It is commonly examined in relation to critical transitions between ecosystem or community types in which dominant competitors or entire landscapes can change in a largely irreversible fashion.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Complex ocean and climate models rely on the principle.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Economic systems can exhibit hysteresis.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] For example, export performance is subject to strong hysteresis effects: because of the fixed transportation costs it may take a big push to start a country's exports, but once the transition is made, not much may be required to keep them going.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] When some negative shock reduces employment in a company or industry, fewer employed workers then remain.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] As usually the employed workers have the power to set wages, their reduced number incentivizes them to bargain for higher wages when the economy again gets better instead of letting the wage be at the equilibrium wage level, where the supply and demand of workers would match.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] This causes hysteresis: the unemployment becomes permanently higher after negative shocks.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The idea of hysteresis is used extensively in the area of labor economics, specifically with reference to the unemployment rate.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] In addition, employers may use time spent in unemployment as a screening tool, i.e., to weed out less desired employees in hiring decisions.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Then, in times of an economic upturn, recovery, or "boom", the affected workers will not share in the prosperity, remaining unemployed for long periods (e.g., over 52 weeks).
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] This makes unemployment "structural", i.e., extremely difficult to reduce simply by increasing the aggregate demand for products and labor without causing increased inflation.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] That is, it is possible that a ratchet effect in unemployment rates exists, so a short-term rise in unemployment rates tends to persist.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] For example, traditional anti-inflationary policy (the use of recession to fight inflation) leads to a permanently higher "natural" rate of unemployment (more scientifically known as the NAIRU).
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The existence of hysteresis has been put forward as a possible explanation for the persistently high unemployment of many economies in the 1990s.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Hysteresis has been invoked by Olivier Blanchard among others to explain the differences in long run unemployment rates between Europe and the United States.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Labor market reform (usually meaning institutional change promoting more flexible wages, firing, and hiring) or strong demand-side economic growth may not therefore reduce this pool of long-term unemployed.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Thus, specific targeted training programs are presented as a possible policy solution.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] However, the hysteresis hypothesis suggests such training programs are aided by persistently high demand for products (perhaps with incomes policies to avoid increased inflation), which reduces the transition costs out of unemployment and into paid employment easier.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Hysteretic models are mathematical models capable of simulating complex nonlinear behavior (hysteresis) characterizing mechanical systems and materials used in different fields of engineering, such as aerospace, civil, and mechanical engineering.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Each subject that involves hysteresis has models that are specific to the subject.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] In addition, there are hysteretic models that capture general features of many systems with hysteresis.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] An example is the Preisach model of hysteresis, which represents a hysteresis nonlinearity as a linear superposition of square loops called non-ideal relays.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Many complex models of hysteresis arise from the simple parallel connection, or superposition, of elementary carriers of hysteresis termed hysterons.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] A simple and intuitive parametric description of various hysteresis loops may be found in the Lapshin model.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Along with the smooth loops, substitution of trapezoidal, triangular or rectangular pulses instead of the harmonic functions allows piecewise-linear hysteresis loops frequently used in discrete automatics to be built in the model.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] There are implementations of the hysteresis loop model in Mathcad and in R programming language.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The Bouc–Wen model of hysteresis is often used to describe non-linear hysteretic systems.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] It was introduced by Bouc and extended by Wen, who demonstrated its versatility by producing a variety of hysteretic patterns.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The most important extension of Bouc-Wen Model was carried out by Baber and Noori and later by Noori and co-workers.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] That extended model, named, BWBN, can reproduce the complex shear pinching or slip-lock phenomenon that earlier model could not reproduce.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] The BWBN model has been widely used in a wide spectrum of applications and implementations are available in software such as OpenSees.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Hysteretic models may have a generalized displacement u as input variable and a generalized force f as output variable, or vice versa.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] In particular, in rate-independent hysteretic models, the output variable does not depend on the rate of variation of the input one.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] Some notable hysteretic models are listed below, along with their associated fields.
[src:olsen-cycle/hysteresis-loop] When hysteresis occurs with extensive and intensive variables, the work done on the system is the area under the hysteresis graph.
[src:olsen-cycle/olsen-cycle] The **Olsen cycle** is a pyroelectric cycle, which was developed between 1978 and 1986 by Olsen and Bruno, by Olsen and Brown, Olsen and Evans, as well as by Olsen et al.
[src:olsen-cycle/olsen-cycle] However, the Olsen cycle avoids the least confusion with its analogous process of the Ericsson cycle.
[src:olsen-cycle/olsen-cycle] The Olsen cycle can generate electricity directly from heat when applied to a pyroelectric material, and has been the most favorable method for the generation of electricity from heat using pyroelectric energy harvesting.
[src:olsen-cycle/olsen-cycle] It consists of two isothermal and two isoelectric field processes in the displacement versus electric field diagram.
[src:olsen-cycle/olsen-cycle] It can be compared to the Ericsson cycle, where working fluid undergoes two isothermal and two isobaric processes in a pressure-volume diagram.
[src:olsen-cycle/olsen-cycle] However, the Ericsson cycle does not include the hysteresis loop, which is essentially a lag between the input of an electric field and the material's output.
